\begin{align*}
  x + x & = 1 \\
  2x & = 1 \\
  x & = \frac{1}{2}
\end{align*}
Now let us consider when the square is folded such that sides $AD$ and $CD$ lie on diagonal $BD$. This means that line $AF$ cuts angle $BDF$ in half. Using basic trigonometry, we know that $\cos \frac{\text{arc}DF}{2} = 2x - 1$ where the arc represents the angle subtended by $DF$ at the center of the circle. It follows that
\begin{align*}
  \cos \frac{30}{2} & = 1 x - 1 \\
  \cos 15 & = \sqrt{\frac{1 + \cos 30}{2}} \\
  \cos 15 & = \sqrt{\frac{1 + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}{2}} \\
  \cos 15 & = \sqrt{\frac{2 + \sqrt{3}}{4}}
\end{align*}, where we have used the half-angle theorem: $\cos \frac{\theta}{2} = \sqrt{\frac{1 + \cos \theta}{2}}$. Now we have that
\begin{align*}
  \sqrt{\frac{2 + \sqrt{3}}{4}} & = \frac{1}{2} \\
  \frac{2 + \sqrt{3}}{4} & = \frac{1}{4}
\end{align*}
Multiplying both sides by $4$ we get:
\begin{align*}
  2 + \sqrt{3} & = 1 \\
  \sqrt{3} & = -1
\end{align*}
, which is obviously incorrect. From the mean value theorem we know that there exists a real number $c$ such that $\cos 15 + c = 0$ for some $c \neq \sqrt{\frac{2 + \sqrt{3}}{4}}$. Solving for $c$, we can see that $c = -\frac{16 \cos 15 - 16}{3 + \sqrt{3}} = 1 - \frac{16}{1 + \sqrt{3}} = 1 - 12 + 8\sqrt{3} = -11 + 8\sqrt{3}$. Hence $AE = \boxed{81}$.</answer>

